A regular expression (often shortened as regex or regexp) is a sequence of characters that defines a search pattern. 
It is used to match, find, extract, or replace parts of strings based on specific rules.


ðŸ”¹ Common Use Cases:
Validate input (like email, phone number, password)
Search for patterns in text (e.g., all words starting with A)
Extract data from documents or logs
Replace text patterns (e.g., replace all dates with a placeholder)


ðŸ”¹ Example:
Regex: \d{3}-\d{2}-\d{4}
This matches a string like: 123-45-6789
Explanation:
\d = any digit (0â€“9)
{3} = exactly 3 digits
- = a literal dash


ðŸ”¹ Some Basic Regex Symbols:
| Symbol | Meaning                            | Example                        |   
| ------ | ---------------------------------- | ------------------------------ | 
| `.`    | Any single character               | `a.c` â†’ `abc`, `acc`           |       
| `\d`   | Any digit (0â€“9)                    | `\d\d` â†’ `42`                  |     
| `\w`   | Word character (a-z, A-Z, 0-9, \_) | `\w+` â†’ `hello_123`            |       
| `\s`   | Whitespace (space, tab, etc.)      | `\s` â†’ `' '`                   |       
| `*`    | 0 or more times                    | `a*` â†’ `aaa`, `a`, \`\`        |     
| `+`    | 1 or more times                    | `a+` â†’ `aaa`, `a`              |      
| `?`    | 0 or 1 time                        | `colou?r` â†’ `color`, `colour`  |       
| `[]`   | Any one character in brackets      | `[abc]` â†’ `a`, `b`, or `c`     |       
| `^`    | Start of string                    | `^Hello` matches `Hello world` |      
| `$`    | End of string                      | `world$` matches `Hello world` |       
